The government wants to stop the torture of "witches" and published a brochure
Women who are stamped as witches in Burkina Faso usually have some common social characteristics.
They are more likely to belong to the older generation, they do not find work - for example, for health reasons, they are single and have no children.
When one of these women "becomes a witch", she is strictly isolated so that she cannot become dangerous to the rest of the village.
"Men are quite rarely affected by this fate."
“Even young and healthy women are spared this, as they help at work and give birth to children,” a religious sister describes the situation in the capital of the West African state of Burkina Faso in a special home caring for more than a hundred women who have been expelled from their communities.
The local government now decided to take action against this abnormal "social measure".
And for this reason, he published a brochure to stop the "witch-hunt".
But the thing has a catch.
"More than 70 percent of all adults in Burkina Faso cannot read," the newspaper "derStandard" pointed out the dilemma of written enlightenment.
Being accused of witchcraft is commonplace in other African countries.
In Ghana, the neighboring country of Burkina Faso, 27-year-old Ammy Hemmahová was tortured to death by three women and two men - they poured it over with petroleum and just set it on fire.
Among other things, the BBC server reported on this incident.
However, the perpetrators claimed that the case was merely a meeting of unfortunate circumstances.
According to her version, oil was inflamed, which was used for ritual anointings.
And that’s after the group tried to “expel an evil spirit” from the woman.
The isolation of "witches" support the people here without regard to their education.
"The Standard" quoted a 42-year-old entrepreneur from Burkina Faso: "Founders of human souls are a danger in the past as they are today," he said.
While the government in Burkina Faso is at least striving to defuse the witch hunt, last year the President of Gambia himself was meticulously involved.
"President Yahya Jammeh initiated a monstrous witch hunt after the death of his aunt, as they allegedly had a share in their deaths and would now try to kill the president himself by black magic."
“He called on shamans from nearby Guinea to help those who, accompanied by police, soldiers and the president’s bodyguard, had indiscriminately kidnapped women and men from Gambian villages and brought them to the president’s farm in Kanilai,” Amnesty International said in its report.
On the farm, the imprisoned people were forced to drink a waste of plants with hallucinogenic effects, which also caused intestinal and renal problems.
Two of the arrested people did not survive the stay on the farm.
It was only due to international pressure that the nearly a thousand prisoners were released.
