The architects saw - the office also includes a kindergarten
The Avriopoint office building in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
But who would expect a mini-kindergarten here, with everything that comes with it: colorful walls, creative furniture, a lot of toys and even a mini-playground on the outdoor terrace.
This kindergarten has been available to Arch.Design employees since last year.
The design and architectural firm Arch.Design, from whose studios come a whole series of well-known Brno buildings, counted on the premises for its company mini-undergarden from the first designs for the new Avriopoint building.
In a wiser sense, because most of his 90 employees (inside) are at the baby boom age and the company is keen that the project managers return to their workplaces as soon as possible.
Along with the possibility to work shorter, kindergarten is another bonus that Arch.Design has to offer its employees in the concept of their social program.
The civil engineers and architects have thus made it easier to bring their demanding profession and childcare under one hat.
The mini-kindergarten is an original idea of the employees of Arch.Design and with the support of the management they managed to win funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs for their project.
The operational mini-kindergarten is funded by the Human Resources and Employment Policy Operational Programme from the European Social Fund and from the Czech Republic’s state budget.
Thanks to this funding (subsidies of CZK 2.8 million), the necessary facilities and equipment were procured and for the duration of 2 years, qualified personnel and operations were taken care of.
After the funding has been exhausted (2 years), the company Arch.Design is obliged to continue running the mini-kindergarten for another 3 years at its own expense.
The preparation of this project took a whole year, with the company Economy Rating providing effective assistance in the processing of applications.
Full-time qualified staff takes care of the children - a nurse and a kindergarten teacher, the kindergarten can attend children without age restrictions, although most of them are over three years old.
And since this is about a mini-kindergarten, only 5 children may be present at the same time, however, the day alternates over several children.
The kindergarten operation is adapted flexibly to the needs of the parents, the children of all employees have the same rights with regard to the use of the kindergarten - regardless of the company hierarchy and their respective position.
Although it is about individual education and care, the program content in the mini-kindergarten is nevertheless comparable to the supporting program of pre-school education.
The children not only play here, but above all they are offered excellent lessons - from basic knowledge to preschool lessons, by the way, they also learn English.
The classroom is not only equipped with toys and creative games, but also with a computer that is available to children.
What's more - the presence of young children in the company contributes to a friendly and positive corporate environment.
The parents can take a look at the children at any time and so the stress of late picking up the children from a far away kindergarten is eliminated.
Parents use their time more productively.
No wonder that natural and loyal employer-employee relationships are also developing here.
Arch.Design thus ranks among the Czech companies that offer clear benefits when recruiting new employees, which are family-friendly and strengthen their personnel marketing through such programs.
A bone house still fascinates after 100 years. Take a look at the interiors of Gaudi
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs like the spine of a dinosaur, and the balconies are torn fish mouths.
This is the Casa Batlló of the Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
From the local inhabitants, the house with its organic shapes was nicknamed "Knochenhaus".
Organic forms, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, tiles and mosaics, the dandruff-like facades and ubiquitous soft lines, all these are typical features of the Art Nouveau style of Antonio Gaudi.
The facade of the house plays with dreamy lines, tender colors and textures reminiscent of nature and living creatures.
It is only on closer inspection that one notices that everything is dominated by geometry, rhythm and thoughtful order.
At night, the entire façade looks even more plastic, dramatic and the special illumination enhances the shine of the colors.
The same swinging lines and entangled shapes also dominate the interior of the house.
Wave-shaped wood copies the window frames, railings, decorative elements of doors, even glance holes and grooves.
The house Batlló in the Eixample district on the bustling shopping street Passeig de Gràcia No. 43 was created by the renovation of a house from 1877, executed by architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, originally insisted on the demolition of the old and the construction of a completely new building, but ultimately he agreed to Gaudí’s idea for an unusual and also cheaper conversion.
However, the Casa Batlló building was not designed by Antoni Gaudí alone.
He worked with the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
It is precisely on his drawing board that the decorations for the representative apartment of the reality owner were created, and the use of mosaics on the facade was also his idea.
However, many other designers and artists also worked on the design of the facade.
The joint work on the designs for Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful collaboration between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaudí’s Casa Milá in Park Güell, which also houses other works by Antoni Gaudí.
Shortly after its completion, the local inhabitants gave the house its organic shapes due to the nickname "Knochenhaus".
Others, in turn, called it the special window opening mechanism because of the "gaining house".
It is also said that at the top of the building is the sword of St. George, patron of Catalonia.
But other sculptural elements also symbolize hidden religious motifs.
Gaudí designed for the house a central heating system unique to the time with ventilation ducts and typical fireplaces.
Something bizarre already seems to her 45-degree inclination.
In his work, Gaudí consistently ignored all the building codes of the time and was by no means deceived by them.
Before the construction began, he obtained the corresponding building permit from the city, but the information he provided about the planned reconstruction was so vague that two years later the city fathers were so horrified at the result when it was completed that they demanded remedy.
Among other things, the councillors also objected to the fact that the building with its pillars even interfered with the public sidewalk.
However, there were no changes, quite the opposite - only fifteen days after the request of the district in this regard, Josep Batlló made an application for approval of the rental of the two highest floors of the house - and it was promptly granted to him.
The owner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor was a social lounge, on the third floor were the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was leased to a jewellery store.
The entire six-storey building passes through a staircase up to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the conversion eliminated all right angles and straight lines and replaced them with curved and curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with a modern concept for the interconnection of spaces.
The social part can be completely connected by opening the salon doors and so a larger society could chat comfortably without having to give up a certain intimacy in more confidential conversations.
The house received a rather unusual roof and two more floors due to Gaudí’s renovation, in addition to a new facade.
Also impressive is Gaudí’s play with the light as well as the blue and white glazed tiles, with which the courtyard is clad and the lighthouses.
The play of these two colors gives all floors of the house the highest degree of light.
He simply took advantage of the principle that white reflects the light better than dark colors, which absorb the sunlight on the contrary.
The Casa Batlló, which was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List in 2005, can now be visited by anyone.
On the first floor, the most spacious and magnificent apartment is made accessible to the public.
The homeowners decided to take this step only in the year on the occasion of the 150th birthday of the famous Creator.
When they found out that this was a fairly profitable business, they kept the sights, even expanded them to other common rooms and the attic, including the roof terrace.
However, the price for visiting the monument is not a cardboard stick, it is 16.50 euros, students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist cards get a 20 percent discount.
This amount exceeds the entrance fees to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to get to know the real atmosphere of the house with its dragon towers, you should try to make friends with one of the residents and visit him at home.
The right mattress and bed frame? Women have different desires than men
Not the best bed frame, but the quality of the reclining area - so mattress and rust make up the good bed.
However, these must complement each other harmoniously in order to meet the wishes of the specific user.
When choosing, many things play a role - the weight, the size, the state of health and, last but not least, the sex of the sleeper.
Equally important is the interior, in which mattress and rust have to be subordinated.
Typical example?
In a weekend house that is not heated regularly, latex mattresses are not well suited, as they take much longer to "get warm".
In addition, they are significantly heavier than conventional polyurethane mattresses.
And - they should be reversed regularly.
If they do not have enough venting ducts in the core and lie on a solid plate, moisture accumulates: it is therefore not excluded that mold forms underneath them.
Of course, what you are used to is also important when it comes to choosing.
If you have been abroad for a long time, where very high mattresses with a soft layer are common, it will be difficult to get used to a low mattress with a hard surface.
"Well, all the hockey players who have come back from the NHL have complained to me that they can no longer sleep properly here."
"For their shredded shoulders, heels and hips, they simply need a soft layer of visco foam (memory foam - a shape memory polymer)."
"I also recommend these to people with diabetes, who suffer from a disorder of the nervous system, so that they can poorly receive the "information" from the joints and skin," explains Sylva Hadamcziková, who specializes in upholstered furniture.
That’s why I bought these visco foam (memory foam) mattresses for many hockey players and other customers years ago.
"Today this is no longer a problem, because such mattresses are offered by the manufacturer Tempur, the Italian company Magniflex or the Czech manufacturer Tropico, among others."
And you don’t necessarily have to be a famous ice hockey player to appreciate the benefits of visco foam.
This "miracle" actually works quite simply.
The foam optimizes its hardness and shape according to the absorbed heat, in other words, it really sticks to the warm body.
Nowhere is it pressing, at night you do not roll around like after a heavy fight.
You just sleep much better.
The viscoelastic foam also offers protection against decubitus (wound burn).
When choosing the mattress size, you should still add the length of the soles to the height of the body, i.e. about 21 to 34 cm.
Men and women, who are about 180 cm tall, need a 210 to 220 cm long bed.
Each of the sleepers should be available at least 90 cm wide, i.e. 180 cm together.
For single beds, for example for singles, 120 to 140 cm are appropriate.
For convenience and for potential visitors.
Otherwise, the following rule of thumb applies to the ideal bed width: "If you lie on your back, there should still be enough room for the slightly angled arms", advises Ing. Helena Prokopová, the guild master of the upholsterers and room furnishers, who for years devoted herself to the problem of healthy sleep and the ergonomics of furniture.
With a double bed, everyone needs their own rust and their own mattress, but be careful when shopping so that the mattresses are the same height.
Otherwise, there is nothing else left but to mount the grid at different heights and this is far from possible with every bed frame.
Foam mattresses should be at least 14 cm high, mattresses with a feather skeleton 15 cm, of which at least three centimeters should be for the mold layer and the fine cushion.
“You shouldn’t feel the feathers with your hand or when you sit down,” warns Helena Prokopová.
Each mattress requires a special type of rust.
Fully upholstered beds with mattress and mattress as well as siamese twins have nothing to look for in the bedroom.
These mattresses can not be ventilated and the cover can not be washed, which is already commonplace today.
And since you lose between 0.2 and 0.75 litres of sweat in a single night, it is clear that after five to seven years, the mattress slowly becomes a huge (and clogged) sieve.
That is also why professionals reject advertising slogans that promise a lifespan of up to 25 years for mattresses, even a lifetime warranty.
Every thing has its if and but.
And therefore a practical advice from the dealers: With mattresses of 120 or 140 cm width, you should not shy away from the hygiene of the washable, removable covers, yet it is advisable to use a mattress protector that can be easily removed and washed.
Even though mattress covers are usually made with a round zipper, so that you get two halves after opening (very important for the washing process and the washing machine size!), manipulation with larger mattresses, especially carried out alone, often seems like the unequal battle between David and Goliath.
Do they have a solid plate in bed instead of a grate?
Get out of here!
Or at most for a bed for unloved guests and for a single night.
Also, they should rather provide the plate with ventilation holes (if there are none already in it) and use mattresses with spring skeleton and 15 cm minimum height with so-called pocket spring core and fine cushion.
Polyurethane mattresses do not belong on such a substrate.
Latex or sandwich mattresses (if necessary also combinations of latex and coconut) are suitable for non-adjustable slatted frames with 14 to 18 spring strips (slats), always with a larger number of slats, i.e. 28 and more spring strips, with lumbar support in the lumbar vertebrae region and the possibility to regulate the slat hardness.
Adjustable slatted frames do not include mattresses with spring skeletons, as they do not respond to the ergonomic adjustment.
In addition to adjusting the stiffness of the spring strips, special flexible shoulder modules are also offered.
This involves a special fastening of the spring strips, which makes it possible to press the spring strips or even to angle them in such a way that they allow the shoulder of the sleeper to sink point-by-point.
Especially for men with wide shoulders an important thing.
There are even mattress manufacturers who have started to use soft zones for the shoulder area in "men's mattresses".
The ladies are also thought of - you treat them to these soft zones in the hip area.
For the most demanding customers, point elastic wing spring systems (Lattoflex) or grids with point elastic contact pads with so-called multi-torsion suspension are designed.
The pressure is distributed over several points, which reduces the voltage.
But - if you use a bad (too large and full) pillow for the right mattress and proper rust, most of the benefits are lost again.
Here, too, a rule of thumb: the pillow should support the head, its tips should only reach up to the shoulders, so that the shoulder muscles can relax.
Ideally, a 50 x 60 cm pillow appears, as the Scandinavians, for example, like.
In the side position, the pillow (together with the shoulder relief zone in the rust or the soft zone in the mattress) should compensate for the shoulder height.
Our modern mattresses have something in common with the former (filled with hay) straw bags.
Modern manufacturers are increasingly using natural materials or at least their admixtures.
Also with mattresses, the new magic word is "bio".
Instead of petroleum raw materials, the production of polyurethane foams is increasingly using natural oils - for example castor and soya oil.
Soya is probably used by all known manufacturers.
"Bio is called mattresses that have a core of materials of pure natural origin," explains Petr Va<0xC5><0xA1>í<0xC4><0x8D>ek from Tropico Plus.
Natural materials are also used in the manufacture of mattress covers - one of the first was aloe vera.
However, you can also treat yourself to microcapsules that spread fresh wood or lavender fragrance while sleeping.
Here, too, you make a difference between man and woman.
While in men, a "cooling" plant extract of birch leaves is used so that the mattress cover can absorb the heat and cool the body, the covers for women have a "warming" effect.
Extracts of red peppers stimulate blood circulation, so the weaker sex gets warm when sleeping.
And today's favorites?
Cold foam mattresses (it has larger pores with destroyed cell structure and is therefore more breathable than commercial polyurethane and also much more flexible).
The combination of the different stiffness (hardness) of cold foams and visco foams creates multi-zone mattresses that know exactly where the head, hips and heels are located.
However, for a high-quality mattress you have to pay 7000 crowns and more.
However, health mattresses are usually charged with lower VAT, as they are considered medical aids.
Gumotex was the first Czech company to gain this advantage.
You see, saving on the mattress and on the rust is not so easy.
Occasionally, there are special offers from manufacturers and retailers that offer two mattresses at the price of one.
For example, the Magniflex brand offers the Duofreeze mattress with covered visco-foam memory for CZK 11,990.
The second one comes for free.
It was the material Tempur that initiated the era of viscoelastic foams with open cell structure and high density at an almost cosmic pace.
No wonder, they were developed for NASA, because the astronauts are exposed to enormous overloads during the launches.
Tempur softens when warm, and in a cool environment it solidifies.
Thus, it adapts perfectly to the human body and distributes the body pressure in an optimal way.
It is therefore not only ideal for preventing pressure fire, but generally increases sleep comfort.
However, viscoelastic foams are not only used in mattresses, but also in other health products, such as, for example, in special foot pads, which are intended to provide relief to the legs and vessels.
Local manufacturers use, for example, the Eucatherm C foams, Twinsaver or similar products.
