A longer index finger than the ring finger means a lower risk of developing cancer
Men whose index finger is longer than the ring finger are obviously at a lower risk of developing prostate cancer.
This is the surprising result of a study published on Wednesday by the British Journal of Cancer.
This is said to be related to the level of the male hormone testosterone.
“Our findings show that the relative length of fingers can serve as a simple test for the risk of prostate cancer, especially in men up to sixty,” said Ros Eeles, a professor at the University of Warwick’s Cancer Research Institute.
The finger could help determine which men should necessarily undergo a prostate cancer test, especially if there are genetic risks or other risk factors, such as family health issues, added Ms. Eeles.
In the period 1994-2009, she and her colleagues in Britain followed more than 1,500 patients with prostate cancer, but also 3,000 healthy men at the same time.
In more than half of the participants in the study, the index finger of the right hand was shorter than the ring finger.
These men had the same likelihood of prostate cancer as 19 percent of those men whose ring and index fingers were the same length.
However, in men whose index fingers were longer than the ring finger, this risk decreased by 33 percent, while in men up to sixty, this decreased by 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers mentioned, which form as early as prenatal age, obviously reflects the different levels of sex hormones to which the child was exposed in the uterus.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index finger.
Previous research found that testosterone accelerates the growth of prostate cancer.
Vaclav Pa<0xC4><0x8D>es, a leading Czech geneticist and former chairman of the Academy of Sciences, told <0xC4><0x8C>TK that he knew this study was fleeting, yet he did not consider the relationship between the length of the finger and the risk of cancer to be "completely proven".
