A man from Malta and one from Brazil want to improve the quality of the ice cream in their bars - and the Canadian housewife Julia comes because her children love Italian ice cream.
Luciano Ferrari explains to the participants the ideal properties of the perfect ice cream.
The decisive factor is not only good taste, but also the silky suppleness and good consistency.
Luciano, however, does not forget the icing on the cake of the national and overall southern superstructure in his training: "Italian gelato is simply the best - and then there is still a lot of romance."
The first step to the production seems quite simple.
Luciano pours the basic ingredients milk, cream, milk powder, sugar and stabilizers into a large mixer that heats everything to 85 degrees with an electronic program and then immediately cools to four degrees.
Then he opens a cock on the machine and comes out a pasteurized white base cream, the basis for all milk ice creams.
Immediately, the lecturer is assaulted with questions: Can you make ice cream only with natural substances without a stabilizer?
How can you let your own desire for experimentation run free?
Luciano warns against being led astray by the Zeitgeist.
Anyone who talks about ice cream "only from natural ingredients" may still have used stabilizers - usually a natural product, such as guar flour from the guar bean.
Of course, you can also make ice without a stabilizer, only then it has to be sold within a day, otherwise it sacks up, and the customer bites on loud ice pellets.
Certain variations in the base mass are allowed.
It gets more exciting with the flavors.
For the taste of the ice cream, Maestro Luciano distinguishes between the ingredients that you buy in the fruit department or in the candy store.
There are also powders and pastes.
"The suppliers will all try to turn you into dozens of flavored additives."
“You should just experiment.”
Either with the fruit sorbets with sugar and fresh fruits.
Or with the ice cream from the white base, which with eggs turns into yellow cream and with cocoa powder as the basis for all kinds of chocolate seductions.
Now the students are allowed to the ice machines.
Luciano has them make four different types of vanilla, chocolate, mocha and hazelnut ice cream - with or without eggs in the base, with more or less vanilla flavouring or other natural additives.
The same experiment will also be undertaken for the fruit ice creams.
More flavourings, more fruit puree - taste is not necessarily better.
Hazelnut ice cream does not necessarily taste nutty if it contains more hazelnuts.
The most popular kiwi ice cream produces the working group that uses more fruits, less water and slightly less stabilizer.
Only a balanced mixture will highlight the taste of a gelato properly, says Luciano.
Ice making is a computational task: If peach puree with a lot of sugar is used, the sugar content in the basic recipe must be reduced.
For lemon ice cream, an extra portion of sugar is needed.
Luciano draws out a device with which he determines the sugar content of the fruit varieties (wines use it to measure the oechsle in grape must).
Fortunately, tables make it easier to calculate.
Making ice cream no longer requires as much physical effort as before.
Not only the device for the automatic production of the base mass helps.
There is also a device in which the finished ice mixture is simultaneously beaten creamy and cooled to minus temperatures.
Despite all the automation, small breakdowns do not fail.
The Brazilian Gustavo treats himself and his classmates from top to bottom with fruit puree when the oversized bar mixer gets out of control.
