The Democracy Routine
The democracy movement in Latin America is becoming stronger, as is the support of private companies.
Crime is a bigger problem than unemployment.
In many parts of the region, the influence of Brazil is greater than that of the United States.
These results came from the Latinobarómetro survey, conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively in The Economist.
This survey has been conducted regularly since 1995 and thus shows the change of opinion in this region.
Two facts are particularly eye-catching in this year’s survey of September and October.
First, the good mood in Latin America
and secondly, the growing interest in democracy and its main institutions.
In many countries on the South American Pacific coast, the democratic movement has increased sharply (see Table 1).
In Peru, for example, where the economy has grown by around 6% annually since 2002, the number of democracy advocates rose from 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
Such a trend can also be seen in Mexico, where the economy has been recovering since the strong collapse last year.
But only half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the region’s most populous countries, are convinced Democrats, which lowers the regional average (see chart 2).
Approximately 44% of respondents said they were satisfied with their country’s democratic practice, which is as many as last year, but 25% more than in 2001 (Graph 3).
Approximately 34% trust the Congress of their country and 45% their government, both of which are similar to last year’s, but show a significant increase compared to 2003 (17% and 24%, respectively).
A decade ago, Latin America’s economic crises undermined efforts to increase democracy.
This may have been due to the fact that the countries of Latin America experienced only a brief recession and recovered quickly.
In addition, the poor were caught by a stronger social network.
(According to reports by the UN Economic Commission for Latin America this week, the poverty rate in Latin America rose only slightly in 2009 and fell by 32% again this year.)
However, there are strong mood differences from country to country (see diagram 4).
Brazil’s strong economy and the popularity of outgoing President Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva are reflected in a widespread thinking of progress.
In Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more noticeable and violent crimes increased, this is less the case.
It is only the second time since the start of the survey that many Latin American respondents see a greater problem in crime in their country than in unemployment (see diagram 5).
Approximately 31% say that either they or a family member were victims of a crime last year, but compared to 38% last year, the figures have fallen, reaching their lowest level since 1995.
The increasing economic performance is reflected in the stronger support of the private and market economies: approximately 71% of respondents supraregionally stated that the private sector is essential for development, compared with 56% in 2007 (see Chart 6).
Approximately 58% said that only the market economy can bring progress to their country, compared to 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela have maintained this view (and 80% are in favour of a private sector), although their left-wing president, Hugo Chávez, nationalized many private companies.
According to 19% of respondents (18% last year), Brazil has the largest weight in the region, followed by the United States (9%, unchanged since last year) and Venezuela (9% compared to 11% last year).
Respondents in Mexico and most Central American countries, on the other hand, see the U.S. as the most influential country, with this role being taken over by Venezuela in the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
An electoral flap
No one expected that the elections on November 28 in Haiti would be perfect.
But the facts far outweighed the fears of the voters who rushed to help the afflicted country.
Overcrowded ballot boxes, multiple votes cast, ballot papers in the Rinnstein, destroyed polling stations and intimidation were only part of the problems.
Voting rooms opened with hours of delay.
Many Haitians, many of whom had become homeless due to the January earthquake, roamed around in search of a choice.
Some finally gave up completely.
A dozen presidential candidates, including some suspected leaders, demanded the cancellation of the election results because of an alleged fraud.
There were some violent protests throughout the country.
Nevertheless, Edmond Mulet, the head of the UN mission in Haiti, described the election as "quite good in many respects."
According to a cautious statement by observers of the Organization of American States and the Caribbean Community, "these irregularities, however serious they may be, do not necessarily invalidate the process."
In other words, the show goes on.
The electoral authority, allegedly committed to the unpopular outgoing President René Préval and his candidate, Jude Célestin, will announce the preliminary results on December 7.
The expected run-off is scheduled for January.
There is still hope in the election.
The two leading opposition candidates, rap musician Michel Martelly and former first-lady Mirlande Manigat, have withdrawn their initial invalidity lawsuit.
If Jude Célestin, who receives little or no voter approval, is declared the winner of the polls by the electoral commission, this could lead to problems.
Due to the cholera epidemic and the fact that more than 1 million earthquake victims still live in tents, low voter turnout was feared.
On election day, many Haitians were prevented from voting due to lack of organization.
Just before the start of the election, about 250,000 ID cards needed for the election had not yet been issued.
There's a lot at stake.
The donor countries see a legitimate, recognized government as an important step in the reconstruction of Haiti.
The Haitians themselves share the same view.
Hidden in the middle
In the weeks following the sudden death of her husband, Argentina’s president, Cristina Fernández, experienced a wave of sympathy that drove her popularity rate up by 20 points to over 50%, the highest since her election in 2007.
However, whether this will help her to be re-elected next year depends on whether the visibly grieving Cristina Fernández is more willing to compromise than her late husband, her predecessor and political partner Néstor Kirchner.
The signs for this are not clear.
Néstor Kirchner, who also steered economic policy after the election of his wife, often drafted budgets that did not fully take into account tax revenues, economic growth and inflation.
This allowed the presidential couple to spend the extra income at their own discretion.
On paper, the Fernández government lost the majority in Congress last year.
But the opposition is divided and Kirchner’s death after a heart attack on October 27 led to further disappointment.
Some regime critics from the ruling Peronists stood behind Cristina Fernández.
But after chaotic meetings (in which one parliamentarian slapped another in the face and others accused the government of bribery), Congress failed to pass the 2011 budget.
“I’m not going to talk about it,” the president said.
The 2010 budget is now valid for next year, which gives the President even more opportunity to spend money at his own discretion.
The economy is running hot: it is likely to grow by up to 9% this year.
The official inflation rate is currently 11.1%, but numerous private estimates - and trade union wage demands - drive the value to almost 30%.
Kirchner, who took office in 2003 when Argentina was shaken by economic crises, declared growth and poverty reduction to be its main goals, not inflation reduction.
He refused to cooperate with the IMF, harassed the private sector, and cleaned the National Institute of Statistics and Census INDEC, which subsequently beautified the official inflation statistics.
Can Fernández take a more moderate path now?
She has called on the private sector and trade union leaders to talk.
And according to official statements, wage increases are to be limited to 18% next year.
The high world market prices for Argentina’s agricultural products have given the economy a strong boost.
However, inflation undermined the growth spurt due to a major devaluation in 2002.
For this reason, Cristina Fernández may want to reconnect Argentina financially with the rest of the world.
Earlier this year, the government entered into an agreement with securities holders who had rejected the country’s previous debt restructuring in 2001.
Now Fernández seems to be pushing for a deal with the donors from the Paris Club, to whom she owes about $6.7 billion.
The Kirchners had always rejected a review by the IMF, as is customary elsewhere.
But last month, Economics Minister Amado Boudou announced that the Fund will provide “technical support” in the creation of a new national consumer price index, which looks like the first step towards purging the INDEC.
It is not known whether Fernández will be politically active even without the support of her husband after her term ends.
If so, it needs the support of the middle class, which is largely fed up with Kirchnerism.
When the Argentinians return from their summer vacation in March, the wave of sympathy that has been brought to them will have ebbed down.
If she wants to win another election, she has to decide whether to quietly undo many of her husband’s political decisions.
Weak applause for China
Taiwan’s voters are slowly approaching a closer connection to the mainland.
What does Taiwan think of its big brother beyond the strait?
On November 27, more than 7.5 million voters, which is 70% of all eligible voters, set out to elect mayors and councillors in the five city districts, a broad assessment of President Ma Ying-jeou.
Through the establishment of groundbreaking business relations, including a partial free trade agreement, Ma himself is a symbol of relations with the mainland. His policy has changed relations with the Chinese motherland for the first time since 1949.
Ma passed the exam, but only briefly.
Although his Kuomintang Party (KMT) appoints three of the five mayors, it did not receive a majority vote.
Instead, the Democratic Progress Party (DPP), which advocates Taiwan’s greater independence, received almost 50% of the votes, and the KMT received 45%.
In a presidential election, this would have been a problem for Ma.
Since his election two years ago, his party’s vote share has fallen by about 8%.
For the first time, the DPP even moved into the city councils together with the KMT.
During the election, there were the usual occurrences in Taiwan such as truck convoys with riot makers, flag-turning mass parades and barely clad dancers.
There was even the compulsory, mysterious attempt at murder.
Sean Lien, the son of Lien Chan and honorary chairman of the KMT, gave a speech on a KMT candidate on the eve of the election,
when a man from the crowd shot him in the face. Lien was wounded and a nearby spectator killed.
Bizarrely, it is not clear whether the shooter wanted to kill Lien or settle a dispute with the candidate.
Regardless, according to Tsai Ing-wen, the leader of the DPP, the attack hampered the election and put the DPP in a bad light, giving the KMT more votes.
Perhaps China was the biggest winner of the campaign.
Remarkably, relations with the mainland were not addressed.
Instead, the candidates debated plans for social housing and job creation.
The Taiwanese love their factual independence and reject China’s military threat.
For this reason, the KMT does not like to put its relations with the government in Beijing in the foreground.
But this time, the DPP also avoided fomenting the anti-Chinese feelings too much.
She responded to the new awareness that Taiwan’s economy cannot survive without China.
Ma, for his part, would like to be confirmed that the majority of Taiwanese are in favour of his China policy.
The government in Beijing will continue to pursue its strategy of enticing Taiwan back into the Community with economic incentives.
China immediately sent a negotiator to Taipei to prepare a summit on investment security and medical cooperation.
It certainly wants political integration, but the most important thing first.
It is better to wait until after the 2012 presidential elections.
The DPP has now reinvented itself.
Two years ago, she was severely weakened: former party leader Chen Shui-bian was imprisoned for corruption.
During his presidency from 2000 to 2008, he strongly advocated absolute independence.
But under Tai’s rule, a new generation of moderate politicians developed and the DPP is fighting for the voices of the professionals and the youth.
Tsai found great approval as the DPP's presidential candidate, like Su Tseng-chang under Chen.
Her party is now doing everything to show that she too is able to build close relations with Beijing.
Tsai plans to create an idea forge as a point of contact between the DPP and China, but this requires unbiased discussions.
Tsai publicly declared that her party was offering a “trusted alternative” to Mas’s accelerated approach to China.
Chen seems very upset about this change.
From his cell, he explained that the DPP candidates would have done better at insisting on Taiwan’s independence.
He even called on the pragmatist Su to renounce the presidential candidacy.
Even without Chen’s intervention, the DPP has a hard time choosing its possible candidate.
The KMT will have to undergo its own self-analysis.
Mas values are bad, despite rapid economic growth; the KMT candidates wanted to run their campaign without him.
The main reasons for his unpopularity seem to be unemployment and the ever-increasing scissors between rich and poor.
According to a KMT spokesman, he will reshape his cabinet and local facilities.
The strong presence of the DPP suggests that Taiwan is only limited in favour of a reapproach.
At the same time, most Taiwanese see economic cooperation with China as inevitable.
According to Antonio Chiang, a prominent columnist, "there is already no going back."
