Arsenic-resistant microbe could enable new forms of life on Earth or elsewhere
The discovery of a foreign species of bacteria that can live on arsenic, among other things, opens up new possibilities for new forms of life on Earth and elsewhere.
Although scientists discovered this unusual bacterium here on Earth, they believe it is a sign that life is possible even without the elements previously considered vital.
"This organism has two possibilities."
"It needs either phosphorus or arsenic to grow."
“This makes it very special, even though it’s almost a kind of ‘foreign’ way of life,” said Paul C.W. Davies of Arizona State University and co-author of the report, which will appear in the online issue of the journal Science on Thursday.
So far, six main elements have been considered vital – carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulphur.
But as the scientists found out, the bacterium in California’s Mono Lake continues to grow even when it replaces phosphorus with arsenic.
"You wonder what else is possible," Ariel D. Anbar, co-author of the report, said.
The discovery is an important step in the search for extraterrestrial life, as scientists need to recognize life and its forms, Anbar said.
The study deals with microbes found on Earth.
The announcement of a press conference, in which no details of the discovery were announced, gave rise to widespread speculation on the Internet that the report could be about the discovery of alien life.
This is not the case.
The discovery "shows that in other planetary systems, organisms can use other elements to trigger biochemical processes and that the 'standard elements' that we believe are absolutely vital are not necessarily fixed," said Charles Cockell, professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute at the Open University of Milton Keynes in the United Kingdom.
Cockel was not part of the research team.
"This work is a novelty because it shows that in basic biochemical processes and structures one element can be replaced by another," Cockell added.
This discovery was not accidental.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA’s Astrobiological Institute, who led the study, chose Mono Lake because of its high arsenic content.
Since arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar, she assumed that microbes exposed to both might be able to replace one element with the other.
“The toxicity of arsenic is primarily due to its chemical similarity to phosphorus.”
"This makes it difficult for organisms to distinguish one element from the other."
"However, the difference is so great that arsenic acts differently than phosphorus, it gets into our biochemical system, where it smears almost everything," explains Anbar.
The researchers exposed the bacterium GFAJ-1 to increasing arsenic concentration and it adapted and grew.
While the microbe grows better in phosphorus, the fact that it can also survive in arsenic shows that an arsenic-based life form can occur naturally, either on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
According to Jamie S. Foster, a lecturer in microbiology at the University of Florida, the idea that phosphorus can be replaced by arsenic is not new, but so far there has been no working example.
Arsenic was more common in the early Earth years, she says, so science has assumed that early life forms used it.
"This gives reason to believe that life may have evolved differently than it did in the early Earth age," said Forster, who was not a member of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Ministry of Energy and the National Health Authorities.
Other stolen exhibition dogs found in Compton
The remaining two of the four exhibition dogs stolen in front of a Bellflower motel were found, according to Thursday's Los Angeles County Sheriff's Office.
The four exhibiting dogs—two Akitas and two Pembroke Welsh Corgis—disappeared on Tuesday when unknowns stole the 2006 Chevrolet Express van where the animals were housed in front of a Bellflower Motel 6 at night, authorities said.
Two of the dogs were discovered on Wednesday afternoon, and the last two on Wednesday evening, says Steve Whitmore, a spokesman for the Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department.
“The good news is, the dogs are well,” Whitmore said.
“They are in good condition.”
"They were returned to their rightful owners."
Whitmore did not give any exact information on the location of the dogs or the circumstances that led to their discovery.
“The investigation is still ongoing.”
"We don't want to say that anymore," Whitmore explains.
"We're following some traces."
The dog owners, Kristina Rickard and David Peek, were not available for information on Thursday.
They received their two dogs on Wednesday afternoon in a district animal shelter in Downey.
Representatives of the sheriff found the van and the two dogs in different locations in Compton.
The Akitas - Trace, a 3-year-old male, and Didi, a 10-month-old female - were uninjured, according to authorities.
But the Corgis Bunny and Peter, who Rickard and Peek wanted to introduce to the competition this week on behalf of their Japanese owners, remained missing until Wednesday evening.
Peek and Rickard, who live in Redding, were in the city this weekend because of the AKC/Eukanuba National Championship in Long Beach, because Trace was supposed to participate in the competition.
As Peek told the Times on Wednesday, the other dogs should take part in other competitions on the days leading up to the AKC/Eukanuba show.
Southern California is a stop on the couple’s nearly one-month tour from dog show to dog show.
On Monday night, Peek and Rickard checked in at the motel.
They often spend the night in motels and park their van in front of their room window.
They took three other dogs - a boxer puppy, a Parson Russell Terrier and a Brittany - into their motel room.
The thick-skinned Akitas and Corgis stayed in the van because it was cooler there.
They left the window wide open so that the dogs had fresh air.
Peek and Rickard reported their car as stolen on Tuesday at 6:00 a.m.
Peek promised anyone who could give an indication of the Corgis a finder's reward. The animals were implanted microchips for identification.
On Thursday, it was not yet clear whether a finder's wages would be paid.
The lion roars again after court approval of the MGM restructuring
After 18 months of turbulence and uncertainty, MGM finally got the green light for a new start.
On Thursday, a New York bankruptcy judge officially blessed the "preparing" believer plan to repay the $5 billion debt and pave the way for the 86-year-old entertainment company for new movies and TV shows.
According to Thursday’s statements, the plan meets the requirements of U.S. bankruptcy law, so nothing will stand in the way of the restart of MGM under the leadership of Gary Barber and Roger Birnbaum, the founders of Spyglass Entertainment.
The number of employees will be reduced from over 400 to about 320.
For MGM, Chapter 11 does not actually enter into force until JPMorgan Chase has completed a $500 million loan to finance the new MGM productions.
At the moment, a consortium of the investment bank, which itself raises $75 million, is heading the company, and the funding is scheduled for mid-December.
The restructuring of the studio began in May 2009 with an order from investment bank Moelis & Co., the company’s management, which was struggling with interest payments of $300 million per year, to help solve its financial problems.
In August, Managing Director Harry Sloan was replaced by Stephen Cooper, a former CEO at Enron and restructuring expert who became known for his work at Krispy Kreme Doughnuts.
Moelis & Cooper’s efforts to solve the financial worries of MGMs and pay out the studio’s more than 140 trustees took longer than expected.
After months of discussions, the parties decided at the end of 2009 to offer the company for purchase.
But the auction attracted only a few bidders and no one wanted to pay the $2 billion demanded by the creditors.
In the spring of this year, everything started from scratch when the MGM team began the restructuring plan, which was finally signed by the creditors at the end of October after months of debates and internal disputes.
If MGM has officially passed bankruptcy over the next few weeks, Moelis and Cooper will receive a multi-million dollar bonus for their work.
The share for Moelis & Co., which has already received $1.2 million, amounts to $9.5 million.
Cooper, who was paid $375,000 per month to run the company, receives a $4 million “success bonus.”
Barber and Birnbaum plan to resume production at MGM. This year, the studio released only one film and created an annual plan with seven or eight films to be released in theaters in early 2012.
They are also planning two films after "The Little Hobbit" in co-production with Warner Bros.
The studio will need a separate bond ranging from $265 million to $275 million for its financial stake in these two films, which will be directed by Peter Jackson.
Investor Carl Icahn, who has financed approximately 18% of the MGM loan, attempted to merge the studio with Lions Gate Entertainment, whose largest shareholder he is.
However, the last negotiations between the two companies resulted in no results.
Tech Toys keeps your gift budget in balance
This year’s favorite among the gifts is the iPad, possibly followed by a Microsoft Kinect video console, both of which can tear a considerable hole in your gift budget.
An iPad costs as much as five BMX wheels for $99, while the price for a Kinect game is about 10 classic jump ropes or about 48 cans of Play-Doh.
But you can save your gift budget.
Recently, in search of three electronics toys under $80, I visited three national toy dealers - a Wal-Mart, a Toys "R" Us, and a BJ's Wholesale Club.
I immediately realized that Moore’s law had come into effect. This year, the technology toys are more powerful and cost slightly less than last year.
And although fewer new toys appear with their own website, the most well-known of this kind, Webkinz and Club Penguin, have a wider offering.
More and more button cell-powered toys are coming on the market, and many contain rechargeable batteries.
Here are some recommendations.
(Unless otherwise stated, all prices are from Toys "R" Us.)
Sing-a-ma-jigs (Mattel, $13, for children from 3 years) are plush figures, the size of guinea pigs, that sing a note when you press on their belly.
Pressing once corresponds to a note, by pressing repeatedly you can play a song.
Several sing-a-ma-jigs sing in harmony.
Attention: Once you have started pushing, you will not be able to stop.
For a combination of message and dance, the Dance Star Mickey (Fisher-Price $60, for children over 2) is the best choice.
Based on the Elmo Live technology developed last year, the animatronic doll offers interplays like 'Simon Says', and thanks to the novel hinge feet with wheel blocking, it masters the Moon Walk.
Children who tested the device use Mickey as a dance teacher, but their parents complained about the lack of volume control.
If you are an 80s child, you certainly remember Alphie, one of the first computerized learning toys.
Now he's back (Hasbro/Playskool, $40, for children over 3), with a bunch of question cards that can turn a car ride into a lesson, with a better knower with car correction function as a teacher.
If you don’t want to entrust your smartphone to your child, here are three independent alternatives.
