Police operations in China are becoming softer
Like a training officer, Tang Shenbin stepped over a city square, checking his nervous subordinates, giving orders with military authority and muted voice.
He wanted his female members of the Chengguan – China’s robust guardians of urban order, feared and despised for their arbitrary raids and their propensity to violence – to impress spectators.
"Standing straight!"
"Look straight ahead!"
"Show them," he whispered, "how pretty girls are!"
Four girls, barely out of teenage age, with white gloves and identical olive-green jackets and pants stood tight.
Four pairs of black pumps were in a straight line.
Four decent hats sat perfectly on the hair held with blue and white striped loops.
"To me, they look average," Mr. Tang remarks contemptuously.
"Models are pretty."
Several governments have already tried to polish the image of China’s city inspectors.
In a city, all new applicants must have a university degree.
The province of Guangdong introduced a bright blue uniform instead of the grey-green one.
Wuhan in Central China replaced violence with low-keyness: In 2009, 50 officials reportedly circled around an improperly positioned food truck and stared at the operator until he packed and left the square after half an hour.
Xindu, a city district in Chengdu with a population of 680,000, wants to fundamentally change the image.
Since 2003, 13 women have been reinforcing the city police forces and have been selected for their appearance, good figure and youth.
They are supposed to give the coarse-sleeping police a softer, feminine aspect.
But unfortunately, Scarlett Johansson would hardly be able to improve the bad image that the Chinese have of these city commands.
Rightly so, the critics.
Unlike the police, these officials are only allowed to enforce the municipal laws by means of fines or other administrative penalties.
But the Chinese media routinely show a different picture.
In January 2008, officials in the province of Hubei beat a spectator to death as he filmed them using his cell phone as they beat down a protest against a dump.
Last year, a training manual for Beijing officials was stolen and published on the Internet, describing how criminals can be beaten without bloodshed.
This year, a Shanghai watermelon merchant suffered brain injuries after a handful of five officials.
A violent video game that can be downloaded from the Internet shows trained officials in China attacking street traffickers.
"Chengguan is scaring the government," the national newspaper China Daily lamented last year, after further controversy over the tactics.
The newspaper called for a “real thorough cleansing.”
Skeptics consider the current approach to be clearly inadequate.
When the district looked for eight female recruits per ad in October, an editorial in the Beijing Evening News asked whether the women had real tasks or should only serve as an optical distraction.
Probably both.
According to the job advertisement, women aged 18 to 22 with good figure and "harmonious facial features" were searched.
They should be above average size - over 1.5m or 5 feet, 2 1/2 inches.
The employment relationship ends when you reach the age of 26.
According to officials, the activity is too physically strenuous for women over 25.
