"All routine."
One reason for this is that the female officials are not allowed to confiscate the merchants’ goods, like their male colleagues.
They can only threaten offenders by reporting them to their male superiors.
This is intended to protect them from public hostilities, to which officials in China are often exposed.
This year, hundreds of residents of Kunming, the capital of Yunnan province, rioted after rumours circulated that Chengguan officials had killed a merchant.
More than a dozen police officers and Chenguan officials were injured in the night incident, 14 government vehicles were overturned or set on fire.
Xindu has so far been spared from such violence.
But unrest cannot be ruled out.
Just two blocks away from the quiet Baonguang Square, where the female officials patrolled that morning, more than 50 people gathered at a street corner.
Officials had confiscated a motorcycle that had been repaired on the sidewalk instead of in a workshop, contrary to the regulations.
The owner screamed Zeter and Mordio.
After 15 minutes of hesitation, the officials with grim face paved the way to their vehicles and continued with the motorcycle and its owner.
Li Xuedong, 40, a coordinator of the male strip, was left behind, turning his white nameplate to remain anonymous.
Like their colleagues, the coordinators - men over 40 - play a purely supportive role.
But they were not trained to present a clean image.
“Sometimes we talk verbally.”
"But sometimes physically," Mr. Li explains soberly.
"Most of the time people start arguing."
Prosecutor will not prosecute Senator Ensign
Attorneys at the Department of Justice have acquitted Senator John Ensign of the allegations raised against him following his affair with a former electoral assistant and his attempt to lobby her husband, the Senator’s lawyers announced on Wednesday.
This decision ends the heaviest allegation against Senator Ensign, the Nevada Republican, who was considered a possible Republican presidential candidate for 2012 until the scandal that made headlines nationwide and dampened his career.
As Senator Ensign's office announced, he was "highly pleased" with the verdict after the one-year investigation.
However, the Senate’s ethics committee could still impose a disciplinary sentence.
According to Ensign’s lawyers, they were informed by the Department of Justice that the investigation against Senator Ensign had been stopped and that there were no further charges in this matter.
The Ministry of Justice did not want to comment on the case.
The verdict was a surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Department of Justice; in their opinion, there was sufficient evidence that Ensign had disregarded the lobbying ban.
Interviews, emails, and other documents first revealed in the New York Times in October 2009 gave rise to the assumption that Ensign Douglas Hampton, one of his constituents, was helping to lucrative orders to buy his silence over an affair with Hampton's wife Cynthia.
Cynthia Hampton served as Treasurer of Ensigns during an election campaign.
Ensign made contact with some political friends to get Hampton to work, and according to the documents and interrogations, he took over Hampton's lobbying for them after hiring.
Since Hampton was on Ensign’s election team recently, he was not allowed to lobby his former employer or the entire Senate for a year.
According to ethics experts, the unusual agreement between Ensign and Hampton, who were close friends before the affair, violated the so-called ban on the revolving door lobbying.
According to the published evidence, "it appears to be a collusion and a violation of the revolving door statutes," said Stanley Brand, a Washington attorney who specializes in defending clients who are targeted by the government.
While the Department of Justice officially refused to disclose the reasons for the decision in the Ensign case, Mr. Brand and other ethics attorneys said the ministry seems very cautious in taking up political charges following a variety of defeats pursued by the media with great interest, including the decision last year to drop the charges against former Senator Ted Stevens for misconduct.
Prosecutors "are obviously terrifying," said Melanie Sloan, the chairman of the association "Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington" (an organization whose goal is to combat corruption in U.S. parliamentary and government circles), a group of lawyers who have brought various charges against Mr. Ensign to court.
"This basically means that senior government officials can now assume that the laws don't apply to them," she added.
Mr. Ensign’s chief defense officer, Paul Coggins, said in an interview that he received a phone call from a prosecutor on Monday and another the next day, informing him that the ministry would not file any lawsuits against his client.
Mr. Ensign's attorneys had cooperated with the prosecutors to convince them that the senator, as his office reiterated in a statement on Wednesday, had "acted in accordance with the law."
Mr. Coggins refused to explain in more detail the legal arguments he had made to the prosecutors.
"I'm not comfortable going into the details of the talks between the Ministry of Justice and me, only to say that we believe we've made the right decision," he said.
Last month, the Federal Election Commission decided to close the investigation into a separate lawsuit by the Ethics Group, according to which a payment of $96,000 from Mr. Ensign’s parents to the Hamptons violated federal election law.
The election commission said there had not been enough evidence that the money was anything but a gift.
NV Energy, a large company in Nevada that supported the senator for a long time, was one of the companies where Mr. Hampton found lobbyist work thanks to the help of Mr. Ensign.
An e-mail from December 2008 proves that after the company continued to lobby Mr. Hampton, Mr. Ensing's chief of staff, John Lopez, had an interview with Mr. Hampton, telling him that he was "tapping" at the Department of the Interior for a matter.
Mr. Ensign also had lunch with Mr. Hampton and another Nevada client, Allegiant Air, and asked the Secretary of Transportation to arrange a meeting on behalf of the airline after Mr. Hampton had stopped lobbying.
Last year, when information about this affair first came to the public, Mr. Ensign apologized to his voters and gave up his position in the Senate, where he had ranked fourth in the Republican rank.
After many months of not being noticed, Mr. Ensign told reporters two weeks ago that he was seeking a third term in the Senate.
In announcing that Mr. Ensign will no longer be the target of police investigations, his press spokeswoman, Jennifer Cooper, the senator expressed hope that the Ethics Committee will very quickly follow the example of the Department of Justice and cease its investigation.
"Senator Ensign is looking forward to continuing his hard work at the service of the people of Nevada," she said.
