Can courtesy connect the separating?
After a campaign of slander and negativity, little politeness has erupted in Washington this week.
Is it the omen of a real two-party cooperation or a moment of illusion before one quickly returns to the struggle of the parties in the capital?
The meeting on Tuesday between President Obama and congressional leaders did not bring a breakthrough in the major issues faced during the so-called "lame duck session", the session at the end of a term in which no decisions are made.
According to all that is heard, it was not a polite discussion between two different sides or a consideration of their shared responsibility to govern, but rather an empty episode of a partisan point gathering.
The public meeting of the President’s Deficit Commission on Wednesday was equally civilized, despite the political differences that continue to exist between the members.
It seems clear that a close interaction over a period of months creates a mutual respect that obscures the ideological divide that continues to separate the members from each other.
This is hardly enough to claim that a new era of cooperation has begun.
Both sides are now in a test phase - in which one demands from the other signs of cooperation and willingness to compromise, while trying to weigh the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters after a renewed party warfare.
Therefore, the Tuesday meeting itself and its assessment by the participants were limited to a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too big and too deep to expect a rapid change in the atmosphere that has prevailed over the past two years.
Whether it’s taxes, donations, health or entitlements, the two sides are miles away from each other.
Last but not least, the November elections in Washington voted mildly for at least a short time.
“No question, the tone has changed,” said Pete Wehner, an official representative of the Bush administration who now works for the Ethics and Public Policy Center.
"This is inevitable after elections.
Elections arouse partisan passions that die again.
And that's good."
On some issues, especially those on the agenda of the "lame duck session," Republicans and Democrats have little choice but to find a solution."
Bush's tax cuts end at the end of the year, and nobody supports that.
Both sides want to find a way to obtain some or all of them, whether temporary or permanent.
Likewise, a compromise on the increase in unemployment benefits is to be expected, if only because Republicans cannot afford to believe that the favored tax cuts for the rich while denying support to unemployed workers.
After the meeting in the White House on Tuesday, the optimism has risen that one can agree on these issues during the "lame duck session" and at the same time ratify the New START Treaty.
However, William Glaston of the Brookings Institution warns that a successful collaboration on urgent issues of the lame duck session "does not necessarily lead to a lasting cooperation between the parties when the new 112th Congress is convened in January.
Instead, he says, a phase of disagreement is more likely, perhaps even inevitable.
“After the things that need to be done are done, this short-term psychology will turn into confrontation,” he said.
Wehner is also skeptical – and this skepticism is shared by many – which leads to genuine cooperation.
"I see a lot of what is happening from today until 2012, as a preliminary fight, or shadow boxing, for the main event of 2012," he said.
The reasons for this have a lot to do with the presentation of the new Republican majority in the White House and with the tea party voters who served their formation.
No matter how concerned the Republican leaders may be that they are playing too high, they know they must try to keep their promises to cut government spending and overturn health care reform.
These party lines are already evident in the first reactions to the Deficit Commission’s recommendations, which include tax reform and raising some taxes, raising retirement age and lowering government spending.
Deputy Chairman Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken over one of the most difficult jobs in Washington and, in their own opinion, have pushed so hard to put the deficit issue on the public agenda that it can no longer be ignored.
But they need 14 of the 18 votes within the Commission to make their plan the official recommendation and they are struggling very hard to get even close to that number.
The greatest opposition is to be found in the elected representatives of the body, since in financial matters, at least today, there is little room for manoeuvre or little sympathy for compromises.
Galston predicts two phases in the battle between the White House and the Republicans in Congress.
The first fight will take place next year in the form of party clashes, when Republicans challenge Obama on the state budget, taxes, and health care system, followed later by a phase of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What will lead to this change?
The public opinion.
It is proven that, despite the partiality of the current election, the majority of Americans still wish the two parties to work together.
If confrontation leads to a dead end, as happened in 1995, then both parties must pay close attention to the public response.
Whoever is condemned to lose will have to change course and seek compromise.
This may indeed be an optimistic view.
Partiality and polarization are greater today than in the mid-1990s, and they seem to be a greater ideological gap between Obama and the Congress Republicans than it was between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans at the time.
At the same time, the activists of both parties see 2010 as a mere prelude to a much far-reaching 2012 election.
From this point of view, the courtesy shown this week may be welcomed by many Americans.
But it will take a lot more effort on both sides to find a common denominator in the issues that still separate the two.
Leaked U.S. document portrays Moscow as a port of corruption
The control of the city is in the hands of the “cleptocracy” and it is passing on part of the bribes and protection money it collects to the Kremlin, according to a memo issued by the US embassy in Russia in February.
Both the police and the state security services are extorting high protection funds so that they can maintain their expensive standard of living in Moscow, it is said.
They collect money not only from legitimate businesses, but also from organized criminal gangs.
Every layer of bureaucracy – what Prime Minister Vladimir Putin has called the “vertical of authority” – takes its share of the money that the ladders are moving upwards.
The memo, sent to Washington under the name of Ambassador John Beyrle, was published by WikiLeaks on its homepage on Tuesday.
The memo is based on sources whose names have been edited.
It was written while Yuri Luzhkov was still Moscow’s mayor, and it accuses him of corruption.
He was fired by President Dmitry Medvedev in October, but there is little evidence that had been cleaned up in the meantime.
Luzhkov and his wife, Yelena Baturina, who owns a well-known construction company, have repeatedly denied corruption allegations over the years, and he has won numerous libel charges against such allegations.
In September, he told a Russian television station when asked about a documentary suggesting he was corrupt: "It's crazy, it's dirty, it's dirty."
> An incredibly large number of Russians believe that their society is corrupt.
But it is unusual that, as the Ambassador's report says, individuals are mentioned, and it is unheard of that being done by a diplomat of a foreign country.
"The direct connection of the Moscow government with crime has led some to call it 'disturbed' and to conclude that the government acts more like a kleptocrat than a government," the memo reads.
Criminal elements enjoy a "kryshna" (a term from the world of criminals / the mafia, literally meaning "roof" or protection) that extends across the police, state security (FSB), the service supervisory authority (MVD) and the prosecutor's office as well as across the entire Moscow government bureaucracy.
Experts have discovered a three-layered structure within the criminal world of Moscow.
"Luzhkov is top priority."
"The FSB, the MVD and the militia are on the second level."
"Lastly, ordinary criminals and criminal inspectors follow at the lowest level."
"This is an incompetent system in which criminal groups close a gap in some areas because the city does not offer any help."
The report goes on to say that the FSB is collecting money from the largest companies and that the police are arresting small businessmen.
One source, it is said, "declared that Moscow's business owners understand that it is best to get protection from the MVD and FSB (and not from organized crime) because they not only have more weapons, resources and power than the criminals, but also because they are protected by law."
"For this reason, protection by criminal gangs is no longer as in demand as it used to be."
The memo notes that while the collection of funds is comprehensive, the protection itself is not very modest; even those who pay are sometimes arrested.
Those who do not pay find their business closed very quickly before - due to the one or the other pretext.
Medvedev has spoken on several occasions about fighting corruption, but at the same time noted that he has made little progress.
The message memo contains descriptions of men who went to the Kremlin with suitcases that were presumably full of money.
"In his fight against corruption, Medvedev must rely on the bureaucrats," said Georgy Satarov, director of Indem, a Moscow expert commission, in an interview recently.
"But he's part of that bureaucracy."
"It is not part of the political class because a political class in Russia no longer exists."
Without politicians, without an opposition, without a separation of powers, he says, corruption is inevitable.
Nationwide, it estimates, corruption costs Russia more than $300 billion a year.
The country ranks 154th in a recent survey on the global perception of corruption by the non-governmental organization Transparency International (countries are listed from "least corrupt" to "most corrupt").
The unveiling of the memo of the American embassy, which happened late in the evening after Moscow, will certainly trigger displeasure within the Russian government, although, as Luzhkov can be accused of Moscow’s mistakes, it can also be a possibility for the Kremlin to claim that one solves the problems.
In an interview with Larry King for CNN, Putin claimed that the WikiLeaks documents could be a fake and reacted furiously to the revelation that American diplomats called him Batman and Medvedev Robin.
"The truth is that it's about our interaction, which is an important factor of domestic policy in this country," he said.
"But to be honest, we didn't expect this to happen with such arrogance, with such pressure and in such unethical ways, you know."
Khmer Rouge Veterans Forced to Confront the Past
In a dimly lit, concrete classroom with dirty and peeling walls, the director of Anlong Veng High School recalls the man who built it, the later Khmer Rouge leader Ta Mok.
"Everyone here loves Ta Mok."
"He was a good leader and he took care of his people," said Sreng Kor Ma, 42 years old.
Because of its brutality during the Khmer Rouge rule known as "the Butcher", the commander remains popular in this remote former Khmer Rouge stronghold in northwest Cambodia, where he built hospitals and bridges, developed infrastructure, and where thousands of former soldiers still live.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge surrender to the government, long-time supporters are being challenged in Anlong Veng.
In April, a local Truth and Reconciliation Forum allowed the victims to publicly confront the people who once supported the regime.
In June, the government distributed a school book telling the story of the Khmer Rouge to children of former soldiers for the first time.
And in July, a UN and Cambodian community tribunal sentenced a former Khmer Rouge member to 35 years in prison for the first time when it sentenced former head of the infamous Tuol Sleng Torture Chamber, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as Duch.
With each of these developments, the fear among Khmer Rouge veterans Alnlong Vengs grew, complicated their efforts to reconcile and reintegrate into the society of Cambodia.
"There is still rejection and fear in the former Khmer Rouge, but they have no power to do anything," said Chhang Youk, head of the documentation center of Cambodia, an independent organization that is investigating the regime.
"For them, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious, but the regime has become a symbol of evil."
"It even divides families."
During the Khmer Rouge rule in Cambodia, between 1975 and 1979, an estimated 1.7 million people were executed or died of disease, overwork or starvation.
When the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew the Pol Pot government in 1979, the remnants of the regime and its military fled to the border of Cambodia to Thailand.
Here they spread unrest until December 1998, when the last movement surrendered.
When Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary waged the guerrilla war from their base in the west of the mountains and jungles of Cambodia, Ta Mok drew the next generation to Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, when a UN-sponsored peace agreement led to the country’s first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began to surrender to the government, leading to the surrenders of Ieng Sary in 1996 and Nuan Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of a natural death in 1998, and Ta Mok, who had not yielded, was arrested by government forces at the Dangrek Mountains in 1999.
He died in 2006 in the prison of Phnom Penh, where he waited for his trial.
When their patrons no longer protected them, most of the former Khmer Rouge fighters fled to rural Cambodia’s tiresome poverty, and many kept the movement in nostalgic memory.
Even though a few Khmer Rouge elite officials retained their local government posts because they laid down their weapons, the ordinary soldiers remained poor, illiterate peasants.
"These people have benefited very little from the surrender," said Sok Leang of the Center for Justice and Reconciliation, which holds public forums throughout Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng.
"They are anchored in the regime's utopian agricultural ideology."
"They grew up without any professional knowledge."
Sor Lim, 55, who joined the Rhmer Rouge in 1974 as a teenager, fought in the jungle for Anlang Veng before settling in 1998 to live a life as a poor rice farmer.
"Life under the Khmer Rouge was good," he said.
"Ta Mok gave everyone something to eat."
"But now life is hard because we have to take care of ourselves."
The ongoing Khmer Rouge Tribunal has also raised concerns here.
At the beginning of next year, the court will try to bring Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, as well as Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer Rouge minister, to trial.
The mandate of the court is to condemn the old leaders and those who are mainly responsible for the atrocities, but it is not said whether it will pursue further acts beyond these four cases.
This has done little to alleviate fears in Anlong Veng.
Current media speculation has focused on Im Chaem, 64, who had been district chief in Manteay Meanchey Province during the Khmer Rouge rule in the late 1970s.
In 2007, she told Cambodia’s Documentation Center commissioner that she was in charge of the construction of the Trapeang Thma Dam, a project in which thousands of forced laborers were believed to have died.
On a hot evening, Im Chaem returned from work in the fields to her wooden house on a dirty street outside Anlong Veng.
When the sun threw long shadows on the dried grass, Im Chaem refused to discuss her past with the Khmer Rouge.
If the court summoned her, she would refuse to leave, she said.
"Cambodia lives in peace and stability," she said.
“If there were no more persecution, there would be war.”
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who fled the Khmer Rouge in 1878, has also repeatedly warned that the situation would become uncertain if the court charged more suspects, although experts and historians discuss this.
"Cambodia must dig a hole and bury the past," he said.
But confronting the past is what Cambodia needs to do in order to move forward, Chhang Youk of the Documentation Center said.
"Reconciliation with the Khmer era means bringing together the broken pieces," he said.
"It is our duty to put these broken parts together so that as everything can understand."
The center created the first government-approved school book about the Khmer Rouge, the 75-page "History of Democratic Cambodia".
It distributed the book in June in Anlong Veng as an appendix to the history book for the High School of the Ministry of Education, which contains less than four pages about the Khmer Rouge.
As often in Cambodia, the young people in Anlong Veng know little about the Khmer Rouge, despite the city’s ties to the regime.
Touch Valeak, 19, a student at Anlong Veng High School, said that the new textbook helps students understand an important part of their story.
But his parents reacted skeptically when he brought the book home to read it.
"My family rejects many parts of the book and the court," he said.
