Zapatero and the Red Line of Germany
Berlin has decided to keep the euro, but at the same time it has set conditions for the entire European Union.
The tensions in the markets have triggered a double response from the government.
On the one hand, José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero has presented new adjustment measures, ranging from tax cuts for small and micro-enterprises, the regulation of temporary employment companies or the abolition of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>426 in support for the unemployed who do not receive unemployment benefits, to the privatization of 49 percent of AENA, the administration of Barajas and El Prat airports, and 30 percent of the state lottery.
On the other hand, the deputy head of government, Elena Salgado, with the help of former prime minister Felipe González, supports the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel as the person in charge, which has summoned the current crisis.
How are these processes to be understood?
It is to be expected that Merkel’s position is not a mistake in her public relations work.
On the contrary, it is a new round in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
In doing so, Germany is adopting a fundamentally new perspective on shaping our future, which conflicts with the maintenance of the traditional traditions of a large part of its partners.
In view of the resistance in Europe, Germany is beginning to speculate on three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first: a strong euro with Germany, Austria, the Netherlands and other countries, while the South would have to leave the euro area.
The second: The reintroduction of the German Mark - although it sounds more like science fiction at the moment - is supported by a large part of public opinion, about 50 percent of the population.
The third: a restructuring of the euro according to German proposals, which means more macroeconomic control; strict budgetary management; punishment of countries that violate the rules; possibly the cessation of payments of some countries and the extension of the costs of potential adjustment measures to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been showing itself for some time now, so there are no excuses.
First in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission created incentives for deficits and the German government pulled out a constitutional reform to prevent this from happening in 2016.
This was the first indication of the divergence between what Germany considered necessary (strict tax plans and stable public finances) and the practices of its European partners, including France.
The second sign was for the Central European country when Merkel painfully postponed the decision to save Greece.
But the fact is that the political consensus in Germany, the public and the public opinion were absolutely against the rescue of Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel comes out with a clear position: she calls for a reform of the European Union agreements to enable the rescue of a country, while at the same time requiring private lenders to bear part of the costs.
This position was interpreted as anti-European because it pushed the Irish crisis and everything that followed.
In the coming months, we will be taking part in the reform of the European Union, which will make these measures possible from 2013 onwards.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
It tells everyone that - even if unpopular measures need to be taken now - the old way of working of the euro will no longer exist from this date onwards.
2013 will be the birth year of a new currency area in which the offending countries can be severely punished, forced to declare themselves insolvent, and in this case the private sector must bear part of the costs.
Germany shows us that we need to take a hard growth course, with high savings and investment rates, moderation of consumption, improved productivity and competitiveness, and positive external trade balances.
The other alternative, which is based on debt and construction with huge holes in the balance of payments, as it was led by Spain in boom times, will simply not be accepted.
The offer is clear.
And we would do badly not understand it.
It is not just about reducing the government deficit to 3% by 2013.
The demands are much harder.
And the worst thing we could do under these conditions is cheat on ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will pass into more calm.
And that we will take advantage of the opportunities that are offered to us by the spring of 2013.
It seems that Zapatero understood this as well, and his double announcement (the promised reforms after the meeting with the big companies last Saturday and the announcement of new measures yesterday) points out that despite the criticism of Merkel, the hypothesis of creating order in her own house has paved its way.
But the red line drawn by Germany is there, and it doesn’t look like anything would change.
Among the options under consideration is that we would have to leave the euro area, which is stuffed with little reputable countries, not exclude.
In this case, Germany could still tell us that it warned us.
Sports and evasion
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos in the game against the Ajax show inventiveness, but not the will to circumvent a sanction.
The exclusion allegedly imposed by two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the November 23 match against Ajax in the Champions League resulted in a lot of ink being shed on whether it was an unsportsmanlike act or not and whether both players should possibly be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is generally known, the two players lost time a few minutes before the end of the game (their team had already clearly won) and played several fouls so that the referee showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid would lead its group, the two players will meet the prescribed sanction at the next league game against Auxerre and thus enter the next stage without any cards.
Finally, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee punished the club’s coach, José Mourinho, with two matches and the players involved with different amounts of money.
Provoking a yellow card under such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is more common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos - the unwritten but adhered to rules in this sport.
Part of the debate about the case is due to the fact that a team of Real Madrid football club (who, in his anthem, claimed nobility and honor and on other occasions punished his players for similar incidents) played the lead role, and to the dramatization by Mourinho, who added one more episode to his long history as a theatrical and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate is about whether this conduct, which is explicitly prohibited by the Statutes, does not conflict with the principles of sport, i.e. whether these acts constitute a circumvention of the rules. In fact, this approach adheres to the Statutes of sport, but seems to circumvent its meaning.
In this case, the damage caused to the sports spirit should be investigated.
The sports spirit defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that was not endangered by these actions, because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to prevent the offending players from taking an unwarranted advantage from the opposing team.
The paradox of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that it does not correspond to what we normally mean by misplaying or bypassing the rule, because circumvention of the rule was not secretly carried out to avoid a sanction, but it should be as conspicuous as possible so that it is punished by the arbitrator.
The players waited and gladly accepted the sanction.
Another question is what kind of advantage the offenders pulled from the deliberate fouls.
It should be pointed out here that the rival was not put in a disadvantageous position or required advantages for the game played, because the obvious result of this action was that the own team had to continue playing with fewer players.
It is also not a useful strategy for the next game, because the club does not have these players.
The advantage is obviously that players will begin the next phase of the Champions League without any cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But it is a long-term, to a certain extent uncertain advantage, as the team could eventually also exit, and players will receive a sanction with this approach and move into the second card cycle, where they will exit with a card less than in the first cycle due to card accumulation.
It is not clear if this is really an advantage.
Ultimately, such practices do not go against the sporting spirit, which also includes strategic decisions in order to make the most of the regulations.
In this case, the players did not want to circumvent a sanction (this would actually be a clear case of circumvention), they were more likely to choose when to undergo it.
They made a strategic decision without evading a punishment or fleeing from it.
Although the boundary between invention and regulatory environment is blurred, I believe that this matter is a clear case of invention.
I have the impression that the polemic has arisen as a result of two factors: because it was about two self-exclusions and because of the nature of the provoked rule transmission.
The damage inflicted on the principles of sport by these actions is less ethical than aesthetic.
