The 188 Interpol countries are instructed to identify and locate Assange "in order to arrest and extradite him provisionally."
Although Interpol cannot order the arrest of an individual affected by a red warning, many member states, according to the organization, consider the red warning as a free letter of arrest – which must be carried out by the national police – especially if they have a bilateral extradition agreement, as is the case with Sweden and England, where Assange is likely to be present.
