China upholds its greenhouse gas reduction targets
China’s representative at COP16 said its country had made tremendous efforts to reduce carbon footprint and would maintain its offer to cut 40 to 45 percent of its greenhouse gases by 2020.
China is holding its offer to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent by 2020, Su Wei, the country’s representative at COP16, assures.
At its first public appearance at the 16th UN World Climate Summit (COP16), Su Wei assured that his country had made tremendous efforts to reduce carbon footprint and to transform its industry.
He explained that in the last four years, his country has invested $245 million to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
On the other hand, he stated that China would not change its goals, but would work with the international community on this matter.
He explained that the Chinese strategy on climate change is divided into four aspects: dialogue, capacity building, institution building and support for pilot programmes.
Progress has been made in all aspects, including the adoption of a new energy law last year that sets targets for reducing gas emissions, he said.
On the other hand, he stressed that in China, the state authorities have worked with those of the central state and the municipalities to achieve the goals of energy saving, efficient use of energy and reduction of emissions.
In addition, he stated, several multi-year plans have already been undertaken or completed, both those financed by the Chinese government and those that received funds from other countries.
For example, he referred to the Energy Effectiveness Programme, which was launched over the last five years and had received investments from the United Nations (UN), the government and private hands.
There is also a provincial-level project on climate change, another on replacing traditional light bulbs with energy-saving bulbs, and another on mitigation and adaptation, he explained.
Martin Krol, the government’s scientific adviser on climate change in this country, confirmed that China’s efforts are far greater than would be generally assumed.
He pointed out that the per capita emission of greenhouse gases in China is six tons per person, while in the United States it is 100 tons. China is responsible for a 9% total contribution to environmental pollution.
It is also making unprecedented progress in the field of energy use: energy efficiency has increased by twenty percent over the last five years, and something else is expected to happen by 2020, he said.
