The U.S. Changes the Rules for Obtaining a Visa
The persons must present themselves to the consulate before their conversation at the service offices for the visa application; costs will be shortened waiting times.
As of January 10, 2011, the procedures for applying for a visa in the United States embassy and consulates will change.
In the new procedure, most applicants will have to present themselves to the Visa Application Service Unit (ASC) before their interview in the consulate.
The ASC staff records the applicant’s biometric data, which is checked by the consulate prior to the interview.
The new procedure has certain advantages for the aspirants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa will decrease, as it is no longer necessary to pay separately for the appointment, processing the visa application and the transport service with which the document is handed over.
The applicant shall make only one payment covering the three services.
The current price remains unchanged: the return of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visas with application (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for hands and investors.
Those who only want to extend their visa do not need to have a conversation in the consulate, they only need to introduce themselves to the nearest ASC, where they will present their documents and take their fingerprints.
As the biometric data is obtained in the ASC, applicants who need a second appointment for the consulate interview are left less time there than before.
Those who apply for the visa in the consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer have to pay the $26 service surcharge.
Further information on the new visa application procedure can be found on the following website: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
