Global Plan to Renew Lighting
The United Nations has proposed a plan to renew lighting for households, trade and industry in 100 countries with a view to achieving a reduction in greenhouse gas (GHG) equivalent to nearly one-third of the additional reduction that needs to be realized to stabilize the Earth’s climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan takes its position in the steps of the concrete major projects that the UN hopes to implement in Cancun to compensate for the absence of mandatory reduction commitments by developed countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, the main problem in the form of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of CFCs released to the Earth due to lighting would be avoided if the white-glowing bulbs, which are still a monopoly of 50 to 70% on the market today, were replaced by fluorescent or, better yet, by LEDs.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This corresponds to an equivalent of 70% of the global fleet’s exhaust emissions.
In Copenhagen last year, major emission companies such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans to reduce global CFC emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, 5 Gt would still have to be deducted from this balance sheet in order to stabilize the climate rise by 2 degrees Celsius from today to 2020, in order to prevent it from becoming out of control.
In the white-glowing bulbs, 95% of the energy escapes in the form of heat, and the remaining 5% produce the light.
With the compact fluorescent bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75%, with the new LED bulbs, this energy requirement is twice as much reduced.
The compact fluorescent bulbs last on average between 6000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those that the manufacturer Philips has launched this week - this company has participated in the UN study, by the way - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a white-glowing bulb, indicating the savings potential of the replacement plan to be applied in 100 countries.
In addition to the fact that ice completely novel bulbs emit very little heat, they can also work with a control resistor.
They do not contain any mercury.
Several specialists have pointed out that compact fluorescent bulbs have reserves because they contain mercury and that they must therefore be disposed of as special waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless the producers provide a receiving point.
However, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet, according to the report, is not the compact fluorescent bulb, but rather the coal-fired power plants that emit significantly more mercury to produce the electricity wasted by the white-glowing bulbs.
In the United States alone, these coal-fired power plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury annually.
The report details the profits that each country would make thanks to this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would save $1 billion annually in electricity purchases and 8 million tons of CO2, the equivalent of 3.5 coal-fired power plants, the construction of which would cost Indonesia 2.5 billion.
