No online games for young Koreans after midnight
The South Korean government is passing a law called “the Ashtray”, which will prohibit young people from playing online games after midnight by blocking them from access, government officials indicated.
A bill calling for online gaming operators to deny access to these games to young people under the age of 16 after midnight will be presented to parliament in December, representatives of the Ministry of Culture and Family Affairs described.
"Many children play these games all night long and then have difficulty learning in school and also living a normal life during the day."
"We believe that this law is necessary to ensure their health and their right to sleep," said Jo Rin, the draft ministerial representative of the French press agency Agence France Presse.
The online games will be available again from 6 a.m.
The manufacturers would have a year to prepare for the application of the law, he clarified.
The government is also considering asking manufacturers to reduce the time limit granted daily for access to these games to those young people whose parents ask for it, the controller added.
It will also provide free programs to those who wish to limit the time spent on the Internet.
South Korea is one of the most "connected" countries, and the newspapers regularly report various events associated with intense internet use.
The country is also an undisputed champion in global online game competitions.
In November, South Korea won four gold medals in the World Cyber Games against 58 other nations.
