Vengeful hackers and busy spies
WikiLeaks has a double meaning.
On the one hand, it has turned out to be an obvious scandal, a scandal that is merely a scandal in the sense of hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes at international level, giving a taste of the future dominated by regression.
But let us proceed in sequence.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that every file created by a secret service (an X-nation) is composed solely of newspaper clippings.
The “extraordinary” American revelations about Berlusconi’s sexual habits are nothing more than what you’ve been reading in every x-any journal for months anyway (except those whose owner is Berlusconi), and the terrifyingly caricatured profile of Gaddafi has been offering her cabaret artists for a long time.
The rule that secret dossiers may consist only of already known news is essential to the dynamics of the intelligence services, and not only in this century.
If you go to a library dedicated to esoteric publications, you will realize that every work (about the Grail, the Mystery of Rennes-le-Chateau, the Templars or the Rose-Cross) repeats exactly what has already been written in previous works.
This is not only because the author of occult texts does not want to publish research (or because he does not know where news about the non-existent would be found), but because those who devote themselves to occultism believe in nothing but what they already know and confirm what they have already learned.
This is also the success mechanism of Dan Brown.
Also the secret files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or limited mind) is also the head of the intelligence service (otherwise he could be whatever, for example, an editor at Libération), who only considers true what he recognizes.
The top-secret information about Berlusconi sent by the US embassy in Rome to the State Department was the same as that published by Newsweek the week before.
So why was such a nuisance made about the disclosures of these dossiers?
On one side, they say what every educated person already knows, namely that the embassies - at least since the end of World War II and since then the heads of government can call each other or take a plane to meet for dinner - have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of some small representation tasks, have turned into espionage centers.
Any viewer of investigative films knows this very well, and it is not out of hypocrisy that one does so by ignoring it.
Nevertheless, the fact of repeating it publicly violates the task of hypocrisy and serves to put American diplomacy in a bad light.
Secondly, the idea that an x-any hacker can tap into the most secrets of the most powerful country in the world holds a significant blow to the prestige of the state department.
In addition, the scandal puts the victims in distress less than the "arrestors".
But let us dedicate ourselves to the profound nature of what happened.
Once upon a time, in Orwell’s time, one could bundle all power like a big brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell’s prophecy could have since proved perfectly correct, where you can control every movement thanks to the phone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the chosen highway and so on; the citizen would become a total victim of the eye of power.
But if one considers what is going on today, that even the secret crypts of power can no longer escape the control of a hacker, the control process ceases to be one-sided and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker – chosen as the avenger of the citizen – can uncover the secrets of power.
But how can a power that is no longer able to keep its own secrets hold?
It is true, Georg Simmel has already said that a real secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that any knowledge of the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is basically a secret free of secret, since it reveals the public sphere; but in the style of WikiLeaks, revealing that the secrets of Hillary Clinton were empty means stealing any power.
WikiLeaks has done neither Sarkozy nor Merkel wrong, but Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this insult that has been inflicted on such a mighty power?
It is obvious that in the future, states will no longer put any reserved information online – that would be like a sticker on the street corner.
But it’s equally obvious that with current technologies, it’s in vain to hope to keep confidential reports secret over the phone.
Nothing is easier than finding out if and when a head of state has moved on a plane and contacted one of his colleagues.
In the future, how could private relationships be maintained only for certain ears?
I know very well that my prediction at the moment sounds like science fiction and novel, but I see myself compelled to imagine the government agents secretly moving busy on uncontrollable routes, carrying their messages with them nowhere but in mere memory, and beyond that the few written information they have got in the set.
The information would be stored in a single copy in closed drawers: basically, Watergate’s espionage attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology is progressing like a cancer nowadays, namely backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet is reconstructing a telegraph with (telephone) wire.
The (analog) video cassettes had enabled the film researchers to explore a film band by band by being able to rewind from back to front and unravel all the secrets of the assembly, while the (numeric) CDs nowadays allow nothing but to jump from chapter to chapter, i.e. in macro portions.
The high-speed trains travel from Rome to Milan within three hours, while it takes three and a half hours by plane including the transfer.
It is therefore not unusual for politics and communication technology to come back to car and horse.
One last observation.
In earlier times, the press tried to understand what secrets were forged between the embassies.
At present, it is the messages that demand confidential information from the press.
Climate: how France speaks out for its financial promises
One year after the Copenhagen Treaty, it is time to examine the fast-resolved financing promises (also called "fast start" or early funding) that have been realised by developing countries.
And already the rough French beautiful shipyards have been uncovered.
With the Copenhagen Treaty, developing countries have pledged to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The EU has pledged <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.2 billion over three years, while France has pledged <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1.26 billion (i.e. 420 million per year).
On the occasion of the opening of COP16, the EU drew all the registers to convince its partners of their commitment to fast-start financing: detailed progress report of their Member States, press conference, major side events, distribution of brochures.
The Transparency Operation is remarkable and just appreciated for its true value: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same at the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>2.2 billion in 2010, which puts it on the right track to respecting its commitment of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.2 billion in 2012.
But when you look into the details, things are a little more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Treaty, this money should be "new and additional" in order to ensure that an additional effort was made without sacrificing public development aid.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what "new and additional" means.
While the EU Commission had proposed harmonisation, certain member states, including France, have blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the guideline they consider best.
For example, the EU Commission has chosen as a benchmark for that of 2009: international funding will be retained, and will add 150 million to the "fast-start" funding for more than three years.
Other countries have chosen similar targets, either in terms of year or in terms of conditions at the level of public development aid.
In return, France considered the funding of "all new projects" of 2010 to be "new and additional".
In other words, there are no benchmarks on previous year’s expenditure or on the global level of public development aid.
Specifically, the total amount of French support for developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease) - France pretends to comply with its commitment regarding "new and additional" financing.
Another crucial element is the breakdown into donations and loans.
There is no rule about it yet, and everyone chooses their computing mode.
Some, such as France, find 1 borrowed <0xE2><0x82><0xAC> as equivalent to 1 donated <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>.
Obviously, this is hard to justify: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans for certain profitable investments can be justified (often tied to emissions mitigation projects based on the most effective technology), it is deceptive to present the euro taken as the equivalent of a donated euro... In addition, only the cost of the loan for the investor country should be counted as the interest rate.
But France has nothing but the following consideration: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by borrowing 91.5% (389.8 million euros) and donating 8.5% (36.1 million euros) - see also the EU document to convince itself.
France is the only country in the EU that uses loans to a large extent.
Germany demands 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) make 100% of their commitments with donations.
In other words, if the vast majority of the European Union spends <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1 to fulfil its obligations, France only spends 10 cents and that means a comparable effort.
Lovely hocus pocus!
All in all, France, in its fast-start financing, operates with a double fraud: partly with the development of the action over time and partly with the reality of the financial deployment.
France manages to make it believe that it has spent 420 million "new and additional" million in line with its promises, saving 36.1 million euros.
The manipulation of the Treasury (since it seems Bercy was the one who conducted the arbitration) could have a double negative effect; once inside the EU (why do the other member states continue to donate if it is enough to borrow?) and then in the negotiations, since the developing countries are not completely deceived...
The chapter of premature financing is only a small question in a relatively short time compared to the totality of discussions on the climate.
But it could be the drop too much in the immense machinery of the UNFCCC.
Let us hope that this will not be the case.
In any case, it is essential to learn the lesson from this first year of early financing.
First and foremost, France could announce a change in its accounting method for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its obligations and balancing justice with the other countries of the European Union.
Above all, however, France could advance the discussions on the subject of long-term financing (a different, decisive and currently discussed topic): one does not escape the question of "accountability" or the accounting method of its loans.
France could change its position to be just as progressive in terms of disputes as it is in other matters.
So hope is based on the new Environment Minister Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprising announcement of France’s fast-start and its vision of “accountability” as well as the use of loans would naturally raise the international trust base necessary for further discussions.
Alarm - Pesticides taken by children
A 10-year-old child consumes 81 different chemical substances over the day, according to a study published this Wednesday by the Association Générations Futures (former movement to protect the rights and respect of future generations).
The association, which explains that its findings "do not represent a statistically significant value given the small number of samples analysed, but rather an illustrative character of the treated problem," had bought the food usually consumed within four, from a approximately ten-year-old child at mealtimes, plus a snack in the supermarkets in Oise and Paris, between July and September.
These typical meals - including the official recommendations of five fresh fruit and fruit parts, three dairy products and 1.5 liters of water per day - were examined as well as lab snacking in search of chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The plate balance is devastating: 81 chemical substances, including 42 classified as potentially or likely to be carcinogenic and five classified as safe carcinogens, as well as 37 substances with endocrinine interference factor, according to studies by several institutions such as the International Cancer Research Center.
"Even if the legal limits for each chemical, individually ingested substance are not exceeded in the near totality of the cases, this survey takes very good account of the fact that the reality in which the consumer is exposed to potentially carcinogenic substances or substances with endocrinine disruptors is worrying," the association notes.
Already at breakfast, the butter and tea with milk alone already contain more than ten of the potentially carcinogenic residues and three safely proven to be carcinogenic, as well as more than twenty residues that can affect the hormone system.
The apple imported from Brazil, intended as a snack for the study, has traces of six chemical substances, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to the green beans from Kenya, including lunch, where the study found traces of a strictly banned insecticide in the EU.
Furthermore, the hack steak, the tuna from the box, even the baguette and the chewing gum were spiked by pesticides and other chemicals.
In the case of tap water, the analyses have revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the salmon steak was the “richest” with 34 identified chemical residues, and even the plastic plate used to warm up the meal in the microwave was not unloaded.
The final risk of this "pollutant cocktail" for the consumer "is likely to be underestimated," the study said.
The Alliance Europe Ecologie-Les Verts (EE-LV), for its part, has proposed a moratorium on the use of pesticides to stop the "growth of civilizational diseases" in view of the urgency of the situation.
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) had identified the presence of residues related to 365 different pesticides identified in fruits and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
